## Political and security developments

### 1. Lebanese Army reports progress on weapons control in the south

The Lebanese Army said it had completed the first phase of bringing non-state weaponry under government control south of the Litani River. It characterized the state monopoly over arms in the area as established in an “effective and tangible way,” although its statement did not explicitly name Hezbollah.

The army said it controlled the area from the Litani River to the Israeli border, excluding territory and positions still occupied by Israel. Remaining work included clearing unexploded ordnance and tunnels. The announcement also suggested that armed groups would no longer be able to launch attacks from the area, according to a Lebanese security source cited in the report.

This is strategically important because sovereign security control is closely linked to:

- sovereign and political-risk assessments;
- insurance and financing costs;
- investor confidence;
- recovery of agriculture and commercial activity in southern Lebanon;
- reconstruction and infrastructure access;
- the prospects for renewed Gulf diplomatic and economic engagement.

**Source:** [Al Jazeera — Lebanon army says phase one of disarming non-state groups in south complete](https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/1/8/lebanons-army-says-phase-one-of-hezbollah-disarmament-in-south-completed)

![Lebanon security developments](https://www.aljazeera.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/2025-12-19T123211Z_1016584993_RC2M5IA0QN5A_RTRMADP_3_ISRAEL-LEBANON-TRUCE-1767857065.jpg?resize=1920%2C1440)

### 2. Governance remains vulnerable to overlapping political deadlines

An analysis published as Lebanon entered 2026 assessed that the country had emerged from complete institutional vacuum but had not reached sustainable stability. It described the first year under President Joseph Aoun and Prime Minister Nawaf Salam as constrained less by routine administration than by structural issues embedded in Lebanon’s political system.

The principal pressure points identified were:

- monopoly of arms;
- border control;
- relations with Syria;
- Lebanon’s place in regional conflicts;
- external pressure on domestic decision-making;
- limited room for state institutions to manage simultaneous crises.

The assessment’s central argument was that the government’s immediate test was not necessarily to resolve all major disputes, but to prevent renewed deterioration and preserve minimum institutional cohesion.

For the UAE, this means that potential engagement will likely remain sensitive to both state capacity and regional-security developments. Political normalization alone may not be enough to unlock large-scale investment unless it is accompanied by enforceable governance, legal certainty, banking functionality, and sustained security.

**Source:** [Institute for Politics and Society — Lebanon in 2026: State Governance under the Pressure of Concurrent Deadlines](https://politicsociety.org/2025/12/29/lebanon-in-2026-state-governance-under-the-pressure-of-concurrent-deadlines/?lang=en)

![Lebanon governance analysis](https://i0.wp.com/politicsociety.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Screenshot-91-1.png?fit=1102%2C725&ssl=1)

## UAE-focused assessment

No verified recent announcement was found concerning:

- a new UAE sovereign or private investment in Lebanon;
- a bilateral trade package;
- Emirati support for Lebanese food security;
- an AI or digital-government partnership;
- an energy or electricity agreement;
- port, airport, transport, water, or telecommunications infrastructure;
- a new UAE humanitarian funding commitment;
- a high-level UAE–Lebanon diplomatic agreement.

The strongest indirect UAE-relevant development is therefore the Lebanese state’s attempt to consolidate security authority. Progress on this issue could improve the environment for future Emirati commerce and development support, whereas continued Israeli attacks, unresolved armed structures, and weak institutional capacity would keep risk elevated.

